{"body": "Bad River Band of the Lake Superior Chippewa Indians Tribal Code. 5.01.130 Classification Criteria (a) Factors to be Considered in Making Classification Determination (1) The critical factors in determining whether a Gaming System is Class II are: (A) Whether the underlying game is a Class II game of Bingo; and (B) Whether the electronic equipment utilized in connection with the game: (i) Is an electronic, computer or other technologic aid, which is permitted within Class II; or (ii) Causes the game to be an electromechanical facsimile of a game of chance. (2) An electronic, computer or other technologic aid: (A) Is defined as electronic, computer, or other technologic equipment used in connection with a game of Bingo that: (i) Assists a player or the playing of a game; (ii) Is not an electromechanical facsimile; and (iii) Is operated in accordance with applicable federal communications law. (B) Includes, but is not limited to, electronic, computer, or other technologic equipment used in connection with a Bingo game that: (i) Broadens participation in the game; (ii) Facilitates communication between and among gaming sites; or (iii) Requires a player to play a game with or against other players rather than with or against a machine. (C) Examples include, but are not limited to, telephones, cables, televisions, screens, satellites, bingo blowers, electronic player stations and electronic Cards. (3) An electromechanical facsimile is a game played in an electronic or electromechanical format that replicates a game of chance by incorporating all of the characteristics of the game, except when for a Class II game such as Bingo, the electronic or electromechanical format broadens participation by allowing multiple players to play with or against each other rather than with or against a machine. (b) Determination that Gaming System is Class II (1) Bingo, as played using a Gaming System, will be determined to be a Class II game if it possesses the attributes of Bingo as set forth in the definition of Bingo in this Regulation. (2) The Tribal Gaming Commission has determined that the following attributes are required by the definition of Bingo: (A) The underlying game consists of: (i) A set quantity of Draw numbers or other designations (hereinafter referred to as \"Symbols\"); (ii) A set number of Cards bearing an array or layout of numbers or other designations available for play in a particular game of Bingo; (iii) Predetermined Game Winning Pattern(s); and (iv) Prizes, including a Game Winning Prize and optional interim and consolation Prizes, as defined under the Rules of Play . (B) The Draw, if conducted using a Random Number Generator, must meet applicable standards for ensuring randomness as set forth in the NIGC Technical Standards or established by the Tribal Gaming Commission. (C) Actual Prize values must be defined before a Prize can be awarded, but need not be defined before the start of a game. (D) A game must be played by a minimum of two players. (3) The Tribal Gaming Commission has determined that the following attributes are consistent with, but not required by , the definition of Bingo: (A) The number of Symbols in a Draw is not fixed; it may be varied from game to game, in accordance with the Rules of Play. Symbols may be displayed, without limitation, as numbers, letters, icons, any other graphic or other enhancement, or any combination thereof. (B) A game may include any number of Cards. The Card may be multi-dimensional. Each Card must have an array or layout of symbols and contain at least two of the Draw symbols. Game Winning Patterns and Prize Winning Patterns can be any configuration of matched symbols on the player's Card. Interim and consolation Prizes also can be awarded for the absence of matched symbols. (C) When playing Bingo, a Draw of a fixed number of Symbols may take place before Cards are purchased by, or distributed to, some or all of the players. Players then compete in a given game by purchasing Cards and then revealing the designations on purchased Cards, so that the pre-drawn Symbols may be Covered. Subsequent Draws may take place to assure that a Game Winning Pattern is achieved. (D) Multiple Prizes may be specified in a game based on, but not necessarily limited to, different Patterns or the number of drawn Symbols required to achieve a specified Pattern. There may be multiple winners, on multiple Cards. Prize levels can also vary for the same Pattern as a function of the player's Consideration for the Card and/or how far the Draw has progressed. Prizes may include interim or consolation Prizes where the Prize is based on the specific order in which the numbers are selected. Progressive Prizes may also be awarded based on specified criteria reflecting sequence or specific characteristics of the Symbols Covered by the player. (E) A player may play more than one Card in a game of Bingo. (4) In determining whether Bingo, as played using a Gaming System, is a Class II game, the Tribal Gaming Commission should not apply any requirements that would: (A) Limit the use of electronic aids to play Bingo, display Cards, Cover Symbols, identify Game or Prize Winning Patterns, or Claim Prizes; (B) Limit the speed of play, Card configuration, or number of Draws in a game; (C) Limit how or when Cards are distributed to players; (D) Limit the sequence of a Draw; (E) Limit how a player Claims a Prize; (F) Limit the type of entertaining display on the Player Interface; or (G) Limit the maximum number of players. ( 9-21-12 ; 11-29-07-190 ; 11-29-07-189 ; 12-29-04-31 ; 12-29-04-30 ; 12-29-04-29 ; 3-21-03-59 ; 6-19-02-295 ; 9-18-01-157 ; 7-2-01-119B ; 3-01-01-49 ; 1-5-00-369 ; 4-8-98-132 ; 9-6-93-81 ; 10-7-92-154 ; 9-20-91-151 ; 4-1-87-39 ; 6-4-86-34 .) Prior Codifications \u00a75.01.130 was formerly codified as 500.35", "num": "5.01.130", "path": "library|Bad River Band of the Lake Superior Chippewa Indians Tribal Code|5|5.01|B|5.01.130", "title": "5.01.130 Classification Criteria", "url": "/us/nsn/badriver/council/code/5.01.130"}
